Following IV ribavirin initiation, viraemia clearance was monitored using the PEID RT-PCR assay designed to detect 1062 bp of the HPIV-2 genome and showed a serial decline in HPIV viraemia with clearance on day 4 of ribavirin therapy (Fig. 2
) along with improvement in myocardial inflammation as reflected by the normalization of the cardiac enzymes (Fig. 3
). The patient tolerated ribavirin with no evidence of haemolytic anaemia or worsening renal function. A transthoracic echocardiogram was performed 2 weeks after ribavirin treatment showed an improvement of the LVEF to 30%. The post-operative recovery was complicated by bleeding that caused a mediastinal haematoma and thrombosis that caused a transient dysphasic stroke. He also suffered from mediastinitis that required a prolonged course of antibiotic and antifungal therapy. After undergoing 6 months of rehabilitation, he recovered his LVEF to 50% and subsequently underwent successful explantation of the LVAD one year after he first presented with myocarditis.
